00:41:36.510 --> 00:41:37.510
we left which really surprised us 'cause we
thought that we might have looked like slackers

00:41:37.510 --> 00:41:38.510
for kind of taking off and vagabonding.

00:41:38.510 --> 00:41:39.510
But actually people were really our bosses
and-and people in the industry were really

00:41:39.510 --> 00:41:40.510
supportive.

00:41:40.510 --> 00:41:41.510
But rather than take a full time desk job
like we normally probably would have, at least

00:41:41.510 --> 00:41:42.510
for me I stayed free lance which is again
not very safe. There's not the steady income

00:41:42.510 --> 00:41:43.510
but it was something that allowed me to still
be working, generating income, be creative,

00:41:43.510 --> 00:41:44.510
but have more time for the other things that
I, that I love doing. So --

00:41:44.510 --> 00:41:45.510
&gt;&gt;Amanda Pressner: I was fortunate I'd kept
up with some contacts that I'd been freelancing

00:41:45.510 --> 00:41:46.510
for before I left and got an offer about six
weeks after coming home for a much higher

00:41:46.510 --> 00:41:47.510
level position.

00:41:47.510 --> 00:41:48.510
I was the senior nutrition editor at Shape
Magazine and it was a job that I felt like

00:41:48.510 --> 00:41:49.510
I couldn't turn down. Like I had the urge
to just freelance like Holly to slow that

00:41:49.510 --> 00:41:50.510
transition, but I'd been an assistant before
and like it's too big of a jump, it's too

00:41:50.510 --> 00:41:51.510
good of an offer not to do. And so I definitely
struggled sitting back at the desk.

00:41:51.510 --> 00:41:52.510
I remember like Holly had said, our year was
so long because it was so rich with experiences,

00:41:52.510 --> 00:41:53.510
and I would get really forlorn those first
few months when I was still at the office

00:41:53.510 --> 00:41:54.510
at nine o'clock thinking, "Oh my God, an entire
day of my life has gone by and I haven't experienced

00:41:54.510 --> 00:41:55.510
it. I've been staring at my computer screen
all day."

00:41:55.510 --> 00:41:56.510
So I think what the trip did for me was it
made me less afraid to go in and address that

00:41:56.510 --> 00:41:57.510
issue with my boss. I think we're all really
afraid sometimes of we don't wanna look like

00:41:57.510 --> 00:41:58.510
the person who doesn't wanna work hard.

00:41:58.510 --> 00:41:59.510
But I-I was able to address that. I was able
to make some changes and was able to go three

00:41:59.510 --> 00:42:00.510
days a week at the magazine which was kind
of unusual.

00:42:00.510 --> 00:42:01.510
But I think because I'd had this trip experience
my editor-in-chief knew that I kinda meant

00:42:01.510 --> 00:42:02.510
business and that if I wasn't happy I wasn't
gonna force myself to stay. I was gonna find

00:42:02.510 --> 00:42:03.510
a job situation that worked better.

00:42:03.510 --> 00:42:04.510
It's not always possible, but I think we've
all kind of taken that commitment to really

00:42:04.510 --> 00:42:05.510
living our lives in the moment as much as
possible like through to this day. So --

